values:
I have officially moved into my new dorm, and it's huge and fabulous. We still need to do some rearranging, but air conditioning, bugless bathrooms, and an all girl suite are things that Brittany and I fucking deserve. Normally an all girl suite would annoy me. And trust me, it does. But knowing that I can go use the toilet and not have to put it down makes the 8 a.m. squealing almost worth it. Did I mention our dorm is awesome? Our closet is fucking enormous, another thing Brittany and I deserve after sharing that horrific closet last year. Squeezing behind dressers and standing on desk chairs to reach our clothing was unbelievably annoying.

My first day on campus and, with the exception of Brittany, I have seen 3 people I recognize. Sarah Heath, Jalon Something Greek, and Meg Edmonds. It's ludicrous how many people on this campus I do not know or even recognize. I spent so long in a little bubble of my friends, that I pretty much know no one left here.&nbsp;

I visited Cristina yesterday and fell in love with her daughter. I think the feelings were mutual, even though Cassie wouldn't sit with me at Perkins. I told her before we left that I wasn't an adult, just a big kid. And so when we went to Perkins and the waitress asked how many, Cassie said, "One big kid, one small kid, and two adults." She's adorable. James and Cristina are moving me into totally dorkdom by getting me into D&amp;D soon. I'm suppose to recruit supercool people to play. I'm working on it.

Brittany and I had one of our famous late night girl talks last night. I missed that, and I feel like alot of my fears from the summer are being resolved already.&nbsp;

I just found out Joel and Curtis are visiting for my birthday! I'm so excited because no one visits me. I've been trying to think of cool things to do while they're here, but I just remembered that it's Selinsgrove.

Would you buy the horse if you could ride it for free? Just an overanalytical thought running through my head at the moment. One that makes me feel quite emo at the moment. So I'm going to attempt to update on the great past few weeks I've had in order to remind myself that even though shit happens, my life is pretty good right now.

Some amount of weeks ago, Ed and Eric came up to Cape Cod for a visit. I stocked up on booze for their arrival, which was about five thirty in the morning Saturday. We braved the early morning and headed to the beach for the sunrise. Unfortunately I did not think to take into effect where the sun rises, so we didn't get to see it over the ocean. Dumb Heather. We went home for a couple hours sleep and woke up late morning to go swimming in the lake. Eric and Ed decided to kayak, which I found mildly amusing. We then headed to the grocery store to plan our barbecue feast. We bought way too much food, but we were hungry. So whatever. We then spent some time in Seaweed Kingdom which is also known as the Mashpee Beach. We fell asleep on the beach, I turned into a radish, and then we returned home to grill up some burgers. That's when the drinking began, and by eleven I had thrown up on myself. I somehow ended up fully clothed in the shower with audience telling me to get out and to take off my throw up shirt. I had the presence of mind to not disrobe until I was in my room. I spent the rest of the night throwing up everything my stomach had to offer. Didn't miss the trash can once. Go me! The next day we had shrimp and steak skewers for lunch and made the hour drive to Chatham so Ed could see real waves. I got massacred by said waves; I still have the scars. On the way home we forgo our original plan to get good seafood and instead detoured in Yarmouth for mini golfing at Pirates Cove. Without a doubt the coolest mini-golf course. Even if Sarah and I did both hit our balls into the little river.&nbsp;

They left shortly after that, and Sarah and I began the incredibly stressful job of packing for our week-long West Virginian camping trip the next day. I got like four hours sleep before I had to drive the 12 hours back to Ohio to drop off my stuff before going on to Burnsville, WV. It was a great camp ground, and we were right on a lake. I swam like six hours a day four seven days. I felt so completely waterlogged. And let's not forget the night of Tragically Drunk Curtis. Sarah and I sat outside in the rain for 2 hours because my uncle didn't want someone puking in his camper. We were soaked. We finally dressed Curtis and got him inside and my incredibly religious grandmother started to pray for him by shaking his head violently. This made Curtis ill again, and he was literally thrown from the camper into a styrofoam cooler where he proceeded to throw up all the water I made him drink. We sat out in the rain for another fourty five minutes before he was safely inside and we were able to shower and change into dry clothes. Of course as soon as we're done it stops raining. The rest of the camping trip was uneventful. I bonded--on multiple levels--with Curtis and Joel the last week before I had to move away for college. I'm going to miss those guys. Joel is like the little brother I never had and Curtis and I had so much in common that he was awesome to be around. Not to mention Kat, Caroline, Ashley, Wes Penn,&nbsp;the drama twins, and Joel the Mole DDR champion of Massachusetts. That last one I honestly&nbsp;won't miss much. Oh yeah, and my Uncle Kevin and Kristy. Joel's mom Kristy is one of the most amazingly liberated and intelligent women I've ever met.&nbsp;

We've been back from WV for a few days, and we've been making up on lost time with Alyssa and Amber. I went to Badfrogs tonight to cheer on Amber in her karaoke contest. One piss tasting Busch made me ill and so I came home to chill. I dont like facebook much anymore. It mostly bears bad news. Don't you love it when your Stalker Feed on facebook tells you something you didn't really want to hear. Announcing one's relationship via facebook is a cruel way to tell the world.

I'm gonna go finish hanging out with Harvey and Grandpa solo, and maybe rent a PPV movie.
